Yes, the thread-safe version can be slower than the non-thread-safe version due to synchronization overhead.

- `Collections.synchronizedList(new ArrayList<>())` uses locks for every operation, which can reduce performance under high contention.
- `CopyOnWriteArrayList` is efficient for reads but slow for frequent writes, as it copies the entire list on each modification.
- `ConcurrentHashMap` itself is fast for concurrent access, but the value (the list) must also be thread-safe.

Choose the thread-safe approach only if you expect concurrent access. For single-threaded or read-mostly scenarios, the non-thread-safe version is faster.

